<TEXT>
ancient rivers that once flowed across an 
earthlike mars may have harbored primitive forms of life that 
flourished briefly before the red planet turned bitterly cold and 
dry scientists say 
steve squyers a planetary scientist at cornell university said 
that most evidence now indicates that mars and the earth were very 
similar shortly after their formation some 45 billion years ago 
and that conditions that led to the formation of life on earth may 
also have existed on mars 
squyers was among the scientists discussing planetary research 
at a meeting monday of the american geophysical union in an 
interview he said the most likely place for finding proof of 
martian life is soil laid down billions of years ago when water is 
thought to have flowed freely across the planets surface 
we know that life developed on earth very early and we know 
that conditions on mars very early were if not earthlike were 
very much more earthlike than they are at the present squyers 
said 
no evidence of life on mars has been found so far in studies by 
satellites and by robot craft that landed there but squyers and 
others believe mars holds out that possibility and even if life 
never evolved there that finding also would be important 
if you dont find life youve found out that despite the fact 
that you had really earthlike conditions they werent earthlike 
enough to produce life he said that will provide more 
information on the type of conditions you must have to enable life 
to develop 
susan postawko of the university of hawaii said most scientists 
studying the planet now accept the idea that water once flowed on 
mars in massive rivers that cut channels across the surface she 
said that idea once was considered outrageous because of conditions 
on mars now 
its virtually impossible to have water flowing on mars under 
the current conditions said torrence johnson a jet propulsion 
laboratory scientist the planet has only seven onethousandths of 
the atmospheric pressure of earth and is very cold water would 
either evaporate or freeze said johnson 
but pictures taken in 1976 by the voyager spacecraft clearly 
showed river beds and this finally persuaded most experts that 
water once covered part of mars surface 
there is really no other way that the channels could have been 
formed said postawko at first it was thought they could be 
lava channels but the way they look is more like water channels 
there is no other abundant liquid that could have formed them 
the question now is she said how did mars change so 
dramatically from the time the rivers flowed 
the most popular consensus is that mars formed and outgassed a 
lot of carbon dioxide forming a greenhouse effect said postawko 
this would keep the planet warm enough for water to flow 
eventually though she said the water would react with the carbon 
dioxide forming carbonates a type of mineral as the mineral is 
formed carbon dioxide is removed from the atmosphere mars cooled 
slowly and dried and the earthlike beginning was snuffed out she 
said 
postawko said this evolution could have occurred in cycles of 
heating and cooling with volcanic action changing the atmospheric 
chemistry and allowing the cycle to restart time after time 
squyers postawko and johnson said few of the questions about 
mars and its history of water and perhaps life will be answered 
until explorers set foot there 
drill samples gathered from the flood plains of some river 
channels sighted in voyager pictures could determine the presence 
of carbonates and in theory could reveal fossilized primitive 
life forms 
squyers said there may also be water still trapped in a 
subsurface permafrost and that core samples taken from high 
latitudes on mars could prove this concept he said pictures 
indicate that at the martian poles there are frozen deposits of 
ice perhaps from water or carbon dioxide samples of this ice 
could give a chemical history of the planet 
ordinary martian soil taken from anywhere on the surface said 
squyers could answer questions about the weather effects that have 
scoured the red surface of mars over billions of years leaving it 
barren while on its sister planet earth life bloomed flourished 
and grew 
squyers postawko and johnson all made presentations monday on 
planetary research at the agu meeting 
