vice president salvador laurel today 
called for a national referendum to decide whether american 
military bases can remain in the philippines after 1991 
the united states and the philippines are holding talks on the 
1947 agreement under which the americans maintain six installations 
here including clark air base and the subic bay naval base 
the outcome is expected to determine whether the manila 
government will allow the bases to remain after the agreement 
expires in september 1991 
in an interview with radio station dzrh laurel said today 
it is to the longrange interest of both nations that we 
should know the sentiments of the filipino regarding the military 
bases we had been arguing and debating on this issue since 1947 
almost 41 years we should end the debate once and for all through 
a national referendum 
the filipino constitution says any extension of the bases 
agreement must be through a formal treaty subject to approval by 
twothirds of the 23member senate where opposition is strong 
the constitution gives congress the option of referring the 
issue to the electorate in a national referendum 
on monday foreign secretary raul manglapus said the americans 
should pay more for use of the bases and if they refuse they 
should go the philippines receives about 180 million a year for 
use of the bases manglapus is chief of the philippine panel which 
is negotiating on the bases 
the chief american negotiator us ambassador nicholas platt 
has said that budget constraints may make it hard for washington to 
provide a substantial increase 
us officials say they are working with japan west germany and 
other american allies to put together a major new aid package for 
the philippines 
president corazon aquino has said she does not want the new aid 
linked to the future of the bases she has pledged to honor the 
bases agreement through 1991 but refuses to say if she will 
support an extension 
