<TEXT>
the british broadcasting corp sold the hulton 
picture library one of europes largest commercial collections of 
photographs engravings and maps to the chairman of a cable 
television company 
michael checkland bbc directorgeneral announced the sale on 
monday but refused to say how much brian deutsch chairman of city 
center cable ltd had agreed to pay for the collection of more 
than 10 million images 
the sale attracted inquiries from around the world and the 
british domestic news agency press association said bids ranged 
up to 56 million 
the illustrations and engravings in the collection date back to 
the 16th century some record the indian mutiny against british 
rule in 185758 
the collection contains a photo of a london bus at the bottom of 
a wartime bomb crater in 1940 a shot of king george v steering a 
yacht in 1924 and cameraman bert hardys classic picture of 
scottish slum children in 1948 
checkland earlier this year described the library as a national 
asset and the bbc insisted the collection must go to what it 
called a good home remain in britain stay open for general use 
and not be broken up 
we have ensured full access for bbc program makers to this 
important historical collection checkland said 
deutsch said the bbc need have no doubt that it has gone to a 
good home and to an owner who cares about its future 
deutsch has formed a board of directors to be responsible for 
the library they include lord quinton chairman of the 
statefunded british library 
the collection owned by the bbc since 1958 earns more than 
400000 a year through the reproduction of its images in 
newspapers journals books films television and videos 
the cashconscious bbc currently reorganizing its commercial 
operations said it wanted to sell because it lacked proper 
resources and expertise to maintain and develop the library 
</TEXT>
