<DOCNO> AP880517-0055 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
for more than a decade a friendly face and 
message painted on the side of joe and gertrude carpenters white 
barn has graced the quiet wood county landscape and greeted 
travelers 
it has served as a landmark and way station of sorts for 
motorists seeking directions or shelter from driving snowstorms 
the barn needs painting now said carpenter a 75yearold 
retired farmer but when the new coats on this summer hes going 
to have the smiling face the friendly hi and the words joe 
and gertie repainted on the side of the barn 
after all the message is a sign of love for his wife who died 
last year after a long illness 
everytime i look at it i think of the old memories and the 
people who stopped and admired it he said 
we were married 51 years its a loss we did everything and 
went everyplace together carpenter said i miss her every 
day 
the 18footwide smiling face is visible from interstate 75 and 
ohio 582 which runs from haskins to woodville in northwestern 
ohio carpenters place is about 20 miles south of toledo 
the face on the barn was his wifes idea mrs carpenter known 
as gertie decided the face would be a fun gift to give her husband 
to celebrate their 41st wedding anniversary in 1976 a year later 
a sign painter added the names joe and gertie 
people laughed when they first saw it but it has become a 
local landmark he said 
the barnyard greeting has often been photographed and has become 
a point of reference when local folks give directions curious 
motorists often visit the carpenter farm to hear the story of the 
anniversary gift 
people stop and say they want to meet joe and gertie they ask 
about the face they say looking at it makes their day weve 
gotten a lot of enjoyment out of it over the years carpenter 
said people tell me dont ever take that face off the barn 
he said his wife was a trusting person who opened the house to 
stranded motorists 
during a 1978 blizzard he said 14 people spent the night in 
the carpenter home 
i remember that like it was yesterday all these people 
couldnt go any place because the highway was closed it was either 
spend the night here or in their cars he said then she got up 
in the morning and cooked breakfast for everybody 
she also had a keen sense of humor 
for some years two mannequins sat on the front porch of the 
carpenter home sometimes the mannequins sat there like a young 
couple courting mrs carpenter he said changed their clothing 
with the seasons 
motorists did double takes as they passed the porch but when 
gertie sold one of the mannequins the courtship was over 
these days carpenter spends most of his time making wooden 
clocks and ornaments two of his three children live nearby 
a few years ago the couple designed their headstone a 
detailed scene of the carpenter farm with the house mailbox and 
barn with the smiling face it also has the friendly hi from 
joe and gertie etched in stone 
she knew what it would look like but she died before she saw 
it he said 
</TEXT>
