<DOCNO> AP880517-0057 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
foreign reporters once lauded for 
their role in the ouster of president ferdinand marcos have gone 
from heroes to heels for alleged unflattering coverage of corazon 
aquinos philippines 
in recent weeks philippine columnists and government officials 
have accused the foreign press of scaring off foreign investors 
depicting manila as a decadent crimeridden slum and even paying 
communist rebels to stage ambushes 
the foreign pressbashing is a far cry from the adulation 
heaped on the international press for its coverage of the 
antimarcos movement 
many filipinos believed the presence of so many foreign 
reporters was responsible for marcos tame response to the february 
1986 uprising which brought his downfall 
a year after marcos ouster a private group with government 
backing even awarded certificates to foreign reporters who covered 
the 1986 uprising identifying them as heroes of the revolution 
philippine media have themselves been sharply critical of mrs 
aquinos stewardship as the country grapples with such problems as 
the communist insurgency widespread poverty inefficient 
bureaucracy deteriorating roads and bridges and a burgeoning 
population 
but the renewed sense of national pride that followed the marcos 
downfall also has shortened the patience of many filipinos for 
criticism by foreigners 
a former communist rebel gemma magallona was quoted as saying 
unidentified foreign reporters paid her group to stage an ambush in 
southeastern luzon and even provided weapons and ammunition 
the report published in the philippine daily inquirer last 
week drew little response until defense secretary fidel v ramos 
said in a television interview thursday that the military had 
evidence the journalists were from a european television network 
later the military identified the crew as from the british 
broadcasting corp the bbc in london denied the allegation and said 
it had no crew in the country at the time of the ambush 
it appeared the charge may have been raised to frighten foreign 
reporters from contacts with the rebels and from visiting their 
camps 
the military has offered no evidence beyond the womans 
allegation but opposition sen juan ponce enrile a former defense 
minister claimed the military had extensive files proving that 
foreign reporters often paid rebels to stage attacks in exchange 
for scoops 
these foreign journalists go to the enemies of the government 
and ask them to ambush soldiers so they can show to the world that 
the country is in a state of turmoil enrile claimed 
sen ernesto herrera called for curbs on the foreign press if 
the former rebels allegation was true 
the immigration chief today said foreign journalists who pay 
communist rebels to stage ambushes against government forces can be 
deported 
if there is sufficent evidence against the aliens and the 
reports can be verified then that would constitute a deportable 
offense under the immigration act immigration commissioner 
miriam defensorsantiago told reporters 
mrs aquinos spokesman teodoro benigno a former bureau chief 
of the french news agency agence francepresse said the government 
would look into the allegation about the bbc 
but when pressed for comment benigno told filipino reporters 
you are journalists yourselves do you believe that thing really 
happened 
the foreign correspondents association of the philippines has 
so far issued no statement on the charge only the latest in a 
series of allegations against the international media 
last week benignos office claimed foreign reporters had 
painted a distorted picture of manila as a crimeridden city by 
reports on killings by communist rebels 
the presidential press office released figures which showed 
manila with a lower crime rate than hong kong tokyo and new york 
filipino critics claim foreign press reports which often focus 
on the communist insurgency coup attempts and political turmoil 
have distorted the image of the country and frightened off foreign 
investors 
the cumulative effect of such garbage that has lately been 
featured in some sectors of the us press could not be lost on the 
american reader who knows less and less of the real philippines 
and her people and more of the seamy side as viewed from the 
gutter wrote columnist hernando abaya in the manila chronicle 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

