<TEXT>
a time magazine article about a company once 
coowned by labor secretary ray donovan was unfair and slanted a 
federal appeals court said as it reinstated a libel suit filed by 
the company 
but the us 3rd circuit court of appeals on monday also 
classifed the company and its chairman as public figures meaning 
they must meet the difficult test of proving time showed actual 
malice before collecting damages 
the suit filed by schiavone construction co of secaucus nj 
and chairman ronald schiavone centers on an aug 23 1982 article 
about a special federal prosecutor reopening an investigation into 
donovans activities while he was labor secretary 
the magazine cited a memo from william webster then fbi 
director saying the name schiavone appeared several times in the 
agencys reports on the 1975 disappearance of former teamster boss 
jimmy hoffa 
the company charged that the article unfairly failed to mention 
that the memo also said the reports linked the company and director 
to no criminal acts 
in november 1986 us district judge h lee sarokin threw out 
the suit saying the reputations of schiavone and his company were 
so poor they were libel proof and could not be damaged further 
by the article 
the appeals court noted schiavones lawyers argued the sting 
of the article did not rest with references to mafia connections 
but in references to schiavone and the hoffa disappearance 
if the jury were to find the sting to be the association with 
hoffas disappearance then it might find that schiavone and scc 
had suffered actual or presumed damages the court said 
the court also affirmed an earlier ruling by sarokin that time 
was not immune to the libel suit under new jerseys fair report 
privilege under the law reporters are shielded from libel suits 
while quoting official reports even if the reports later prove 
inaccurate 
the appellate court ruled that time forfeited the privilege 
because the reporter intentionally left out a portion of the fbi 
memo 
we believe that times omission presents a clear example of an 
unfair report that does not deserve the qualified privilege to 
reproduce a libel circuit judge edward r becker wrote for the 
threejudge panel 
the last paragraph in times article combines selective 
quoting and innuendo to provide a very different message than the 
article would have conveyed had it included the exculpatory 
material becker wrote 
the time story questioned why the fbi during its routine 
investigation of donovan before his senate confirmation withheld 
information from a special prosecutor 
