stocking up in anticipation of huge price increases later this 
month newspapers reported today 
coffee disappeared first from belgrade shops city authorities 
said they would dip into emergency reserves to supply 250 tons of 
coffee to consumers the vecernje novosti daily reported 
local media reported about 80 percent of the countrys 
manufacturers have announced they will boost prices when the 
government lifts a price freeze later this month new prices are 
expected to be about 50 to 70 percent higher than the current ones 
the government has announced a 3 percent increase in the price 
of coffee effective immediately one kilogram of coffee now costs 
13 
belgrade authorities said the sale of detergents jumped by 100 
percent cooking oil by 70 percent flour by 50 percent and sugar 
by 45 percent compared to the week before 
shelves storing these items are virtually empty said 
vecernje novosti 
city officials called on yugoslavs not to stockpile goods 
saying the practice could create even worse shortages 
the price freeze was to end may 15 but was postponed until 
later this month after the government announced it had failed to 
secure about 300 million in emergency credits from the west 
the government said the funds were a condition for yugoslavia to 
receive an expected 14 billion in new loans from the 
international monetary fund western governments and banks to 
finance the countrys 20 billion foreign debt 
failure to secure the initial funds led the government to delay 
the lifting of the wage and price freeze until an agreement on the 
loans is reached 
the lifting of the sixmonth price freeze will also coincide 
with a package of economic measures intended to reduce yugoslavias 
170 percent inflation rate europes highest and help the country 
repay its foreign debt 
the economic package includes ceilings on wage increases 
measures against the further decline of yugoslavias currency the 
dinar the lifting of import barriers and the gradual closing down 
of industries which show losses 
the austerity program is likely to contribute to a further drop 
in yugoslavias living standards which have already fallen by 
onethird since 1980 labor unrest which in 1987 produced over 
1500 strikes is also expected to grow 
</TEXT>
