the former president of a credit clinic has 
agreed to stop claiming that he can improve peoples credit 
ratings the federal trade commission announced tuesday 
jeffrey roberts former head of creditrite inc of palmyra 
nj signed a consent order promising not to misrepresent his 
ability to improve credit ratings and agreeing to honor refund 
promises 
the agreement settles charged that roberts and the company made 
false and misleading claims that they could substantially improve 
the credit standing of individuals 
creditrite operated 29 credit repair franchises in 13 states 
and the district of columbia until it ceased operations in 1987 
the ftc said the company charged individuals 500 to 700 for its 
services 
under terms of the agreement roberts must give any future 
credit repair clients a written notice that they have no legal 
right to have accurate information removed from their credit files 
and telling them how long such information can be kept on file 
currently credit bureaus can report negative information as 
long as it is correct for seven years and bankruptcies for 10 
years any individual can request to have inaccurate information 
removed from their file 
