<TEXT>
ethiopias two biggest rebel groups 
tuesday accused the government of killing more than 400 civilians 
in separate bombing and tank attacks calling it the worst massacre 
in a dozen years 
the clandestine radio of the eritrean peoples liberation front 
claimed hundreds of people died in a may 12 government attack on 
the village of sheib in eastern eritrea 
eighty people were crushed by tanks and 320 were killed by 
gunfire reported the voice of the broad masses of eritrea 
monitored in nairobi 
the rebels said troops then looted and set fire to sheib and six 
nearby villages destroying 2000 houses and forcing 8000 people 
to flee 
the radio said it was the greatest mass killing by 
government troops since 1976 it gave no details 
eritrean rebels have been fighting the central ethiopian 
government in addis ababa for 27 years in africas longest civil 
war 
in tigre eritreas southern neighbor and home to a 14yearold 
civil war rebels said ethiopian warplanes bombed the ancient 
capital of axum on sunday for the second time in two weeks killing 
a teenage girl and wounding five other people 
the repeated bombardment of tigrean towns and population 
centers is part of the regimes scorched earth policy and total war 
against the tigrean people the tigrean peoples liberation front 
said from their london office 
the tigrean rebels said zemzem adem 15 was killed in the 
bombing and her younger sister zeniba adem was severely wounded 
the other injured included 6yearold zera senai mesfin they said 
axum 340 miles north of addis ababa was capital of an ancient 
northern ethiopian kingdom that flourished from 500 bc until the 
seventh century the area has been in rebel hands since a major 
offensive in march 
the tigreans said government jets also bombed axum april 3 but 
there were no casualties 
on saturday president mengistu haile mariam declared a state of 
emergency in tigre and eritrea allowing the government to designate 
certain areas as prohibited western diplomats said the move was 
part of a planned government offensive against the northern rebels 
wartorn northern ethiopia is the most remote part of the 
country and access to the area by outsiders is limited 
the war has disrupted a massive westernfinanced relief effort 
to save 32 million drought victims 2 million of whom are believed 
to be in rebel territory and beyond the reach of emergency aid 
</TEXT>
