a top education department official on tuesday 
blasted a rand corp study partially financed by his agency that 
acquitted teacher unions of obstructing school reform 
chester finn jr an assistant secretary whose office of 
educational research and improvement paid 35000 for the study 
said the rand researchers engaged in very selective reporting 
and did a poor job of analyzing events in the six states they 
examined 
the report teacher unions and educational reform 
concluded despite charges to the contrary teacher unions have 
not been a major obstacle to educational reform 
it did not name names but education secretary william j 
bennett has accused unions of trying to hijack the reform 
movement with demands for more money without stricter 
accountability 
the rand study said unions generally have accommodated reforms 
even if they had misgivings about such initiatives as career 
ladders for teachers 
i dont think the report is an accurate depiction of the state 
of affairs finn said in an interview weve got a much longer 
list of hijacking episodes than they have of accommodationist 
episodes 
the rand study reviewed 151 teacher contracts and examined the 
impact of reform laws in six states arizona california florida 
georgia minnesota and pennsylvania 
finn said unions have fought bitterly with governors in 
tennessee texas new jersey and indiana over career ladders 
competency tests for teachers alternative certification methods 
and other reforms the teachers union in st louis mo is in 
court battling a plan to tie teacher evaluations to student 
performance he noted 
even if the unions accommodated reforms that seemed inevitable 
finn said going along with something only after its clear you 
cant beat it is scarcely a very positive thing to say about a 
professional organization 
he claimed unions are still engaging in guerrilla warfare 
against reform efforts aimed at upgrading the quality of teaching 
the rand report said rankandfile teachers are unwilling to 
accept reforms as a substitute for breadandbutter improvements in 
their basic working conditions 
