the us navy on tuesday marked the first 
anniversary of the iraqi air attack on the uss stark by dropping a 
wreath in persian gulf waters where the frigate was hit by two 
errant missiles with the loss of 37 lives 
during the ceremony a navy chaplain offered a prayer and a 
sevenman rifle team fired a salute from the deck of the destroyer 
uss stump 
we pause amidst our duties to honor men of stark who laid 
down their lives in service to country and to dedicate ourselves 
as fellow shipmates to the great task of protecting peace and 
righteousness among all nations said the chaplain lt cmdr 
jerry mcnabb 
flanked by a 24man honor guard in dress whites a chief petty 
officer and a seaman the oldest and youngest members of the 
stumps 325man crew tossed the wreath over the side cmdr 
constantine l xefteries the destroyers skipper also spoke 
mcnabb had attended survivors after the may 17 1987 attack 
according to naval sources who provided details of the ceremony 
the stump is one of the 16 us warships serving in the gulf 
having recently arrived as a temporary replacement for the frigate 
samuel b roberts the roberts a sister ship of the stark was 
severely damaged by an iranian mine last month 
the stark was hit by two exocet missiles fired by an iraqi 
warplane as it conducted what the navy said was a routine patrol 
mission in the central gulf 
ravaged by fires fed by unspent missile fuel and hot enough to 
melt the steel decks the 3700ton warship was saved from sinking 
by its crew and salvage tugs that rushed to its aid 
the main damage and most casualties were in the combat control 
center and the enlisted crew quarters as the missiles slammed into 
the 445foot vessel amidships just behind and below the bridge on 
the port side 
iraq apologized for what it called a mistaken attack saying the 
f1 mirage fighterbombers missiles were intended for an iranian 
vessel 
the united states officially accepted baghdads explanation but 
demands for compensation for the ship and families of the dead 
crewmen have yet to be settled 
the starks captain and tactical action officer were retired 
from the navy after an official inquiry held they had failed to 
protect the ship sufficiently from the possibility of attack 
the stark homeported at mayport fla is nearing completion of 
