<TEXT>
interior secretary donald p hodel rejected 
the advice of an advisory committee tuesday and declared a national 
historic landmark the maryland farm where whittaker chambers hid 
the pumpkin papers that convicted alger hiss 
chambers was a figure of transcendent importance in the 
nations history hodel said in a speech to the heritage 
foundation a conservative group 
hodel a staunch conservative who like many in the modern 
conservative movement acknowledges an intellectual and 
philosophical debt to chambers himself nominated pipe creek farm 
in westminster md for landmark status 
westminster is about 30 miles northwest of baltimore the farm 
is operated by chambers son john 
he was supported by the staff of the national park service 
which administers the landmark program 
william penn mott director of the service wrote hodel that the 
staff concluded that whittaker chambers was exceptionally 
significant and that the farm represents that significance with the 
requisite degree of historical integrity 
both the maryland state historic preservation office and a 
professional review committee including outside historians 
supported the designation but the advisory board of the national 
park service on april 26 opposed it 
the board cited the service guideline that 50 years should 
elapse before designation of landmarks to give historians time for 
an objective assessment 
i appreciate that the board disagrees but i do not chose to 
follow its advice in this instance said hodel 
the chairman of the advisory panel daniel jordan was 
philosophical about the secretarys rejection of its advice 
im surprised and disappointed i felt the advisory board had 
met its obligation in a serious manner and had made the correct 
decision said jordan who is head of the thomas jefferson 
memorial foundation in charlottesville va in a statement relayed 
by an aide 
but i also recognize that the board is responsible only for 
making a recommendation and that the final decision always rests 
with the secretary of the interior 
bruce craig cultural resources specialist for the national 
parks and conservation association a private group that lobbies 
for policies to benefit the parks said interior secretaries had 
disregarded the 50year rule before but it was the first time in 
memory that one had overruled the advisory board 
hodels disregard of the 50year rule constitutes a threat to 
the preservation program insofar as it represents a politicization 
of the program craig said 
it was 40 years ago that chambers then an editor at time 
magazine accused hiss a former state department official who had 
