<DOCNO> AP880517-0258 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
twenty years ago the chairman of a major company 
asked a professor to help him evaluate the executives who worked 
for him especially in regard to what might be expected of them 
the professor eugene e jennings had developed a reputation 
for analyzing corporations and the people who manage them and 
already had advised many chief executives on executive personnel 
matters 
this assignment was different before he could project the 
performance that might be expected of the executives he would first 
have to determine who they were and what made them do the things 
they did 
it required him to develop an analytical framework should he 
fail to develop one he feared he might find himself doing what he 
had often criticized in the news media that of judging a top 
executive on style alone 
style is perhaps the least important aspect of an executive 
says jennings professor of business administration at michigan 
state university and author of many books on institutional 
leadership 
style is a reflection of temperament the degree to which a 
person is for example vociferous brusk patient passive and so 
on but the person who focuses on style never gets to 
substance jennings says 
he believes it is much more rewarding and revealing to focus on 
the persons personal and functional values or operating 
principles the individuals own view of his or her role their 
technique of decision making 
evaluate executives on that basis and you will have a much 
fuller picture of the person he advises the media stock market 
analysts authors executive headhunters and others who he says 
customarily fall into the style trap 
he refers to his system as vtrs 
v is for personal and functional values every executive he 
says has certain values that foretell behavior if you want to 
find out about your boss values ask yourself what would most 
upset my boss if i did it 
president jimmy carter for instance wanted nothing given to 
him that had not been formatted or put into a logical format from 
which he could make judgments jennings says 
t is technique of decision making for example is the chief 
analytical or intuitive 
some chiefs says jennings require lots of data and get 
involved in intense analyses others might need little data some 
need many sources others few 
r is for role every executive has a view of his or her job that 
goes beyond the usual job description it is that persons 
essential justification for being the boss 
what is his or her driving force how does the boss view his 
or her role in history what will history say about the boss 
s or style is easy to spot says jennings since it involves 
outward and obvious personality traits it lends itself to colorful 
and even dramatic descriptions but seldom does an analysis of 
style get far beneath the surface 
jennings observes that style analysis cannot help a reader 
understand how for example 10 executives fail to get along 
because they have incompatible operating values disparate views of 
each others roles and employ decisionmaking techniques that 
require varying amounts of time information and people 
he suggests that those called upon to analyze the uniqueness of 
executives use his guide or a similar one as a means of avoiding 
the style trap 
he warns against books by socalled insiders such as 
speechwriters speechwriters are provided peepholes in which they 
learn just enough in order to write the story but not enough to 
understand the full content of an event 
he criticizes a current book call me roger by a former 
general motors speechwriter as an example of the emphasis on 
style if you want to know what makes the chairman of gm tick you 
wont find it there he says 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

