<TEXT>
a us district court judge on tuesday ruled 
that allegheny international inc could hold its annual meeting 
friday as originally planned renewing a proxy fight for control of 
the troubled company 
allegheny said the judge stayed a preliminary injunction issued 
monday by the us bankruptcy court which barred the meeting from 
taking place for 90 days 
as a result of the new ruling the meeting is scheduled for 
friday pending a further hearing on the case in us district 
court 
tuesdays federal court ruling will be in place until the judge 
conducts another hearing wednesday on the bankruptcy courts 
preliminary injunction 
the ruling means the proxy contest between a group of dissident 
shareholders and the company is again under way 
the struggle to wrest control of allegheny international which 
is reorganizing under chapter 11 federal bankruptcy protection from 
creditors is led by spear leeds amp kellogg a new york investment 
banker that has invested about 30 million in the companys 
preferred stock 
the bankruptcy court had issued its injunction at the request of 
alleghenys unsecured creditors committee the court ruled the 
pittsburghbased company could call its annual meeting after it had 
submitted its chapter 11 reorganization plan to shareholders and 
creditors but before they had voted on it 
speer leeds asked us district judge alan bloch to overturn the 
bankruptcy court ruling and reinstate the proxy fight 
pittsburghbased allegheny international manufactures consumer 
products including sunbeam and oster appliances 
